metadata.name: Theatergoers #30
metadata.description:
Simple black and white blobs align to create delicate stories of an audience at their local theater. Follow their eyes in each piece to get started, but don't stare for too long——that's rude.

- press 's' to save the image at its current resolution
- press 'h' to say hello

20% of primary sales will be donated to https://www.cityarts.org/ and minters will receive a small royalty for all secondary sales.

metadata.name: Asta Collection #119
metadata.description:
In the creation of "Asta," a tapestry of mathematical precision and mythological grandeur unfolds before the viewer. The name itself is an ode to the Old Norse term "Ástríðr," which combines "ás," or the divine, with "fríðr," the beautiful. Much like the gods and goddesses of Norse mythology, "Asta" dwells in a space where disparate forces like unity and fragmentation or chaos and order find harmony.

The visual core of the artwork is composed of concentric circles meticulously shaped from individual spheres. Each circle, akin to the realms over which Norse gods presided, is a universe unto itself, yet all function as part of an overarching cosmic design. The deities of Norse lore were complex beings, embodying both virtues and flaws, and such dualities reverberate through each sphere and orbit within the piece.

Serving as a backdrop for this celestial assembly is a canvas marked by signs of distress and decay. This reflects the concept of entropy inherent in Norse cosmology—often symbolized by the serpent Jormungandr biting its own tail to form a circle. Circles that appear to have lost their center drift aimlessly, reminiscent of gods who have fallen from grace, thereby capturing the unpredictable and imperfect nature of existence.

"Asta" is not merely a visual spectacle; it's an invitation to embark on a philosophical exploration. As viewers traverse the delicate balance between intricate patterns and intentional anomalies, they are compelled to confront the eternal dualities symbolized in Norse mythology—such as order and chaos, the finite and the infinite, and the divine and the mortal.

For those who engage with it, "Asta" serves as more than just an art piece. It becomes a poetic meeting with the sublime and a tribute to the complexities that both life and mythology bestow upon the human experience.

Controls
========
The controls are as follows:
- Press `t` - 370 x 200 png output (thumbnail)
- Press `1` - 650 x 1200 png output
- Press `2` - 1300 x 2400 png output
- Press `3` - 1950 x 3600 png output
- Press `4` - 3250 x 6000 png output
- Press `5` - 5200 x 9600 png output
- Press `6` - 7800 x 14400 png output

Please note that the larger the output, the longer it will take to generate.

metadata.name: Hashed Cities #351
metadata.description:
This token generates a deterministic set of minimal, abstract buildings of varying widths, heights, transparencies, and patterns, assembling a skyline view of your own unique imaginary city. Each city comes with its own randomized city day.

Each mint has a native setting (Day or Night) which combined with the current time of viewing influences real-time movements of celestial bodies in your mint, e.g. on a mint with the Day setting, the sun will only appear when viewed during the day. The piece will re-render every minute.

The individual strokes of this token feature some of my latest developments of an algorithm that generatively simulates the texture of print imperfections. They are randomized at each render to give it a unique character. Note that depending on the complexity of each mint, some renders may introduce a brief pause. The aesthetics are greatly inspired by plotter art of early computer artists such as 'City Painting' by Grace C. Hertlein.

Made in p5js
Created Nov 2021
Artist: @Yazid

metadata.name: Coupé Décalé #36
metadata.description:
Coupé-Décalé is a type of popular dance music originating in Côte d'Ivoire (Ivory Coast).
The term Coupé-Décalé means cut-shifted in french.
A name that perfectly defines the process used in this generative series.

Artist: Estienne
Dec. 2021 / Jan. 2022

metadata.description:

NOTE TO COLLECTORS:

This token will be sold as a Dutch auction. Every 5 minutes, the price will change based on the following schedule:
20 / 15 / 10 / 5 / 2 tez

After that, the price will remain fixed at 2 tez.
If there are tokens remaining after 72 hours, they will be burnt.
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

0xFoif

Inspired by Tyler Hobbs' water color studies and the splitting algorithm of 0xDrue, 0xFoif is a collection of interplay between a strong grid with clear cut splits and a blurriness introduced by multiple transparent layers.

Zürich/Quito, January 2022

metadata.name: Celebrate the D2 #363
metadata.description:
Fixed a bug in the original project.
It can now actually output uniform patterns :-)
 
A fun free mint to celebrate 500 followers on Twitter.
The project is open for 24 hours, for all to mint.
And after that, the remaining editions get burned.

The base shape is a "super ellipse", made famous by (among others) danish inventor and polymath Piet Hein.

metadata.name: Flowers #252
metadata.description:
This project is inspired by natural flowers.
Flowers and foliage in the piece are arranged randomly, but they follow a regular pattern, as flowers do as they grow.
Initially, flowers are produced randomly and without color. Afterwards, the pieces are painted according to the color palettes, so that viewers can feel the effect of colors.
Each piece is processed until the frame part is reached.

Fully generated by p5.js

Press 's' to get a 3000x3000 px PNG file.
